SIMPLE: stomach
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stomach
<hw>Stom"ach</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stomak</ets>, F. <ets>estomac</ets>, L. <ets>stomachus</ets>, fr.
Gr. <grk>sto`machos</grk> stomach, throat, gullet, fr. <grk>sto`ma</grk>
a mouth, any outlet or entrance.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>
<def>An enlargement, or series of enlargements, in the anterior part of
the alimentary canal, in which food is digested; any cavity in which
digestion takes place in an animal; a digestive cavity. See
<er>Digestion</er>, and <cref>Gastric juice</cref>, under
<er>Gastric</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The desire for food caused by hunger; appetite;
<as>as, a good <ex>stomach</ex> for roast beef</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence appetite in general; inclination;
desire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He which hath no <qex>stomach</qex> to this fight,⟦br⟧
Let him depart.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Violence of temper; anger; sullenness; resentment;
willful obstinacy; stubbornness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stern was his look, and full of <qex>stomach</qex> vain.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This sort of crying proceeding from pride, obstinacy, and
<qex>stomach</qex>, the will, where the fault lies, must be bent.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Pride; haughtiness; arrogance.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was a man⟦br⟧
Of an unbounded <qex>stomach</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stomach pump</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a small
pump or syringe with a flexible tube, for drawing liquids from the
stomach, or for injecting them into it.</cd> -- <col><b>Stomach
tube</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a long flexible tube for
introduction into the stomach.</cd> -- <col><b>Stomach worm</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the common roundworm (<spn>Ascaris
lumbricoides</spn>) found in the human intestine, and rarely in the
stomach.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stomach</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stomach
<hw>Stom"ach</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Stomached</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stomaching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. L. <ets>stomachari</ets>,
v.t. & i., to be angry or vexed at a thing.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
resent; to remember with anger; to dislike.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lion began to show his teeth, and to <qex>stomach</qex> the
affront.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Parliament sit in that body . . . to be his counselors and
dictators, though he <qex>stomach</qex> it.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bear without repugnance; to brook.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stomach</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stomach
<hw>Stom"ach</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be angry.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stomachal</ent>⟦br⟧
